Q7: Create a GitHub Actions pipeline to automatically build and push a Docker image of a Python app to Docker Hub

Step 1: Create Project Folder (File Explorer / VS Code)

Create a new folder in your system
Example location:
C:\Users\Jeevanjerald\Documents\Devops Ex7

Open this folder in VS Code or File Explorer

Step 2: Create Application File (app.py)

Create a file named app.py and paste:

from flask import Flask

app = Flask(**name**)

@app.route('/')
def home():
return "Docker CI/CD Pipeline Working!"

if **name** == '**main**':
app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)

Step 3: Create requirements.txt
Create a file named requirements.txt
Add:
flask

Step 4: Create Dockerfile

Create a file named Dockerfile

Add:

FROM python:3.10

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

CMD ["python", "app.py"]

Step 5: Create GitHub Actions Workflow File

Create folders:

.github
.github/workflows

Inside workflows, create file:

docker.yml

Paste:

name: Docker CI Pipeline

on:
push:
branches: ["main"]

jobs:
build:
runs-on: ubuntu-latest

```
steps:
- name: Checkout Code
  uses: actions/checkout@v3  

- name: Login to Docker Hub
  uses: docker/login-action@v2  
  with:
    username: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}
    password: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_TOKEN }}  

- name: Build Docker Image
  run: docker build -t ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/myapp .  

- name: Push Docker Image
  run: docker push ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/myapp  
```

Step 6: Create Docker Hub Access Token (Browser)

Open Docker Hub

Login with your account

Go to Account Settings → Security

Click "New Access Token"

Give name: github-actions

Copy and save the token

Step 7: Create GitHub Repository (Browser)

Open GitHub

Click "New Repository"

Enter name (example: Devops-Lab)

Do not initialize with README

Click Create

Step 8: Add Secrets in GitHub (Browser)

Open your repository

Go to Settings

Click "Secrets and variables" → Actions

Click "New repository secret"

Add:

DOCKER_USERNAME = jeevanjeraldm
DOCKER_TOKEN = your_access_token

Step 9: Push Code to GitHub (Terminal)

Open terminal in your project folder

cd "C:\Users\Jeevanjerald\Documents\Devops Ex7"

git init
git remote add origin https://github.com/JeevanJeraldm/Devops-Lab.git
git branch -M main
git add .
git commit -m "Added Docker CI pipeline"
git push -u origin main

Step 10: Verify Execution (GitHub)

Open your repository

Click "Actions" tab

Open "Docker CI Pipeline"

Check if build is successful (green tick)

Step 11: Verify in Docker Hub (Browser)

Open Docker Hub

Check your repository:

https://hub.docker.com/r/jeevanjeraldm/myapp

Step 12: Run Docker Image Locally (Terminal)

docker pull jeevanjeraldm/myapp

docker run -p 5000:5000 jeevanjeraldm/myapp

Open browser:

http://localhost:5000

Execution Summary
Code pushed to GitHub
GitHub Actions triggered automatically
Docker image built using Dockerfile
Image pushed securely using access token
Application can be run locally using Docker
